{"title_page": "Carolina wren", "text_new": "{{Good article}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Carolina wren\n| image = Carolina Wren1.jpg\n| image2 = Thryothorus ludovicianus song.ogg\n| image2_caption = Recorded in [[Cape May, New Jersey]], US\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22711450/0 |title=''Thryothorus ludovicianus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Thryothorus\n| parent_authority = [[Louis Jean Pierre Vieillot|Vieillot]], 1816<ref name=David/>\n| species = ludovicianus\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1790)\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision_ref = <ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n| subdivision = {{collapsible list|bullets = true|title=<small>List</small>\n|''T. l. berlandieri''\n|''T. l. burleighi''\n|''T. l. lomitensis''\n|''T. l. ludovicianus''\n|''T. l. miamensis''\n|''T. l. nesophilus''\n|''T. l. tropicalis''\n|''T. (l.) albinucha'' \u2013 White-browed wren}}\n| range_map = Thryothorus ludovicianus species distribution map.svg\n| range_map_caption = Range of the Carolina wren (''T. ludovicianus'')\n| synonyms = ''Sylvia ludoviciana'' <small>(Latham, 1790)</small>\n| synonyms_ref = <ref>{{cite book|title=Check-list of birds of the World. Volume IX.|editor=Mayr, E.|editor2=Greenway, J.C. Jr.|year=1960|publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology|place=Cambridge, Mass. |url=https://archive.org/stream/checklistofbirds91960pete#page/408/mode/2up|pages=409\u2013410}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Carolina wren''' (''Thryothorus ludovicianus'') is a common [[species]] of [[wren]] that is a resident in the eastern half of the [[United States|United States of America]], the extreme south of [[Ontario]], Canada, and the extreme northeast of [[Mexico]]. Severe winters restrict the northern limits of their range while favorable weather conditions lead to a northward extension of their breeding range. Their preferred habitat is in dense cover in forest, farm edges and suburban areas. This wren is the [[List of U.S. state birds|state bird]] of [[South Carolina]].\n\nThere are seven recognized subspecies across the range of these wrens and they differ slightly in song and appearance. The birds are generally inconspicuous, avoiding the open for extended periods of time. When out in the open, they investigate their surroundings and are rarely stationary. After finding a mate, pairs maintain a [[territory (animal)|territory]] and stay together for several years. Both sexes give out alarm calls, but only males sing to advertise territory. Carolina wrens raise multiple broods during the summer breeding season, but can fall victim to [[brood parasitism]] by [[brown-headed cowbird]]s, among other species. Some populations have been affected by mercury contamination.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe Carolina wren was first described under the name of ''Sylvia ludoviciana'' by [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] in 1790.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>{{#tag:ref|Johann Friedrich Gmelin wrongly associated the Carolina wren with the European wrens under the name ''Motacilla troglodytes'' (originally coined by [[Carl Linnaeus]] in [[Systema Naturae]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Linnaeus|first=C.|authorlink=Carl Linnaeus|title=Systema Naturae per Regna Tria Naturae, Secundum Classes, Ordines, Genera, Species, cum Characteribus, Differentiis, Synonymis, Locis. Tomus I. Editio Decima, Reformata|volume=v.1| publisher=Laurentius Salvius|location=[[Stockholm|Holmiae]]|language=Latin| year=1758|page=188|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/727076#page/208/mode/1up}}</ref> in 1788.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Harding|first=J.|title=Journal of the Academy of the Sciences of Philadelphia: Volume IV, Part I| publisher=[[Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University|Academy of Sciences of Philadelphia]]|location=[[Philadelphia]]|year=1824|pages=28\u201329|url=https://archive.org/stream/journalofacademy04acaduoft#page/28/mode/2up}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} [[Louis Jean Pierre Vieillot]] considered all wrens under the genus [[Troglodytes (bird)|''Troglodytes'']] and called the Carolina wren ''Troglodytes arundinaceus'' but placed it subsequently in a separate genus ''Thryothorus'' (initially misspelled ''Thriothorus''\n<ref name=David />) that he created in 1816.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Auk|title=A synopsis of the genus commonly called Anorthura|author=Oberholser, Harry C.|year=1902|pages=175\u2013181|url=https://archive.org/stream/jstor-4069309/4069309#page/n1/mode/2up|jstor=4069309|volume=19|issue=2|doi=10.2307/4069309}}</ref> ''Thryothorus'' is of [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] origin from the combination of ''thryon'' (rush, reed) and ''thouros'' (derivative of verb ''throskein'' to leap up, spring, jump at) which means 'reed jumper'; its [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] ''ludovicianus'' is a post-classical [[Latin]] term for ''Ludovicus'' (derivative from [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]]) that means 'of [[Louisiana (New France)|Louisiana]]' that identifies the locality of the specimen collected near [[New Orleans]].<ref name=\"Sandrock\">{{cite book|last=Sandrock|first=James|title=The Scientific Nomenclature of Birds in the Upper Midwest|publisher=University of Iowa Press|year=2014|page=144|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_I3zAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA144|isbn=978-1609382254}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/coueschecklistof00couerich#page/31/mode/1up|page=31|title=Coues check list of North American Birds|edition=2nd|year=1882|author=Coues, Elliot|publisher=Estes and Lauriat|place=Boston}}</ref>\n\nThere are seven recognized subspecies of the Carolina wren:<ref name=\"Brewer15\">{{cite book|last=Brewer|first=David|title=Wrens, Dippers, and Thrashers|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2001|pages=132\u20134|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-r35SXfm9BYC&pg=PA134|isbn=978-0-300-09059-8}}</ref><ref name=\"Carolina or White-browed Wren\">{{cite web|title=Carolina or White-browed Wren (Thryothorus [ludovicianus or albinucha])|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=CB5469E1211E7EFF|publisher=AviBase|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n*''T. l. ludovicianus'' (Latham, 1790) \u2013 Southeast Canada (Southern Ontario, irregularly in Eastern and Southern Quebec) and the eastern United States (Southern [[Wisconsin]] and [[New England]] southward to [[Texas]] and northern [[Florida]]).\n*''T. l. miamensis'' '''Florida wren''' (Ridgway, 1875) \u2013 Florida from approximately 30 degrees ([[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]]) region southward through the rest of the state.\n*''T. l. nesophilus'' (Stevenson, 1973) \u2013 [[Dog Island (Florida)|Dog Island]] in Northwestern Florida.\n*''T. l. burleighi'' \u2013 '''Burleigh's Carolina wren''' (Lowery, 1940) Offshore islands off of the [[Mississippi]] coast: [[Cat Island (Mississippi)|Cat Island]], [[Ship Island (Mississippi)]], and [[Horn Island (Mississippi)|Horn Island]].\n*''T. l. lomitensis'' \u2013 '''Lomita wren''' (Sennett, 1890) southern Texas to the extreme northeast of Mexico ([[Tamaulipas]]).\n*''T. l. berlandieri'' \u2013 '''Berlandier's wren''' (S. F. Baird, 1858) Northeastern Mexico (eastern [[Coahuila]], [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], and southwestern Tamaulipas)\n*''T. l. tropicalis'' \u2013 Northeastern Mexico (eastern [[San Luis Potos\u00ed]] and southern Tamaulipas).\n*''T. ludovicianus'' is traditionally placed within its own genus as its only representative of North America, but recent DNA work suggests it is closely allied with the [[Bewick's wren]].<ref name=Mann/> A distinct population in the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] of Mexico, [[Belize]], [[Nicaragua]], and in [[Guatemala]] is treated as a separate species, either known as Cabot's wren or white-browed wren (''Thryothorus albinucha'').<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"TAMU\"/> It is considered a subspecies of ''T. ludovicianus'' by some authors, however.<ref name=\"Carolina or White-browed Wren\"/>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:95%; line-height:95%\n|1={{clade\n |1={{clade\n  |1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Grey-barred wren|Campylorhynchus megalopterus]]''\n   |2=''[[Cactus wren|Campylorhynchus brunneicapillus]]'' }}\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=''[[Bewick's wren|Thryomanes bewicki]]''\n   |2={{clade\n    |1='''''Thryothorus ludovicianus ludovicianus'''''\n    |2='''''T. l. albinucha''''' }} }} }}\n |2={{clade\n  |1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Peruvian wren|Cinnycerthia peruana]]''\n   |2={{clade\n    |1=''[[Fawn-breasted wren|Thryothorus guarayanus]]''\n    |2=''[[Buff-breasted wren|Thryothorus leucotis]]'' }} }}\n  |2={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n    |1={{clade\n     |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n       |1=''[[White-breasted wood wren|Henicorhina leucosticta]]''\n       |2=''[[Grey-breasted wood wren|Henicorhina leucophrys]]'' }}\n      |2=''[[White-bellied wren|Uropsila leucogastra]]'' }}\n     |2=''[[Musician wren|Cyphorhinus arada]]'' }}\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Spot-breasted wren|Thryothorus maculipectus]]''\n     |2=''[[Coraya wren|Thryothorus coraya]]'' }} }}\n   |2=''[[Sinaloa wren|Thryothorus sinaloa]]'' }} }} }} }}\n\n==Description==\n[[File:CarolinaWren-23SEP2016.jpg|alt=Carolina Wren|left|thumb|335x335px|Carolina Wren in [[Greenville, South Carolina]]. ]]\nAt {{convert|12.5|to|14|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, with a {{convert|29|cm|in|abbr=on}} wingspan and a weight of about {{convert|18|to|23|g|oz|abbr=on}}, the Carolina wren is a fairly large wren; the second largest in the United States species after the [[cactus wren]]. Among standard measurements, the [[Wing chord (biology)|wing chord]] is {{convert|5.4|to|6.4|cm|in|abbr=on}}, the [[tail]] is {{convert|4.5|to|5.6|cm|in|abbr=on}}, the [[Culmen (bird)|culmen]] is {{convert|1.4|to|1.8|cm|in|abbr=on}} and the [[Tarsus (skeleton)|tarsus]] is {{convert|2|to|2.3|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> [[Sexual dimorphism]] is slight with males being larger than their mates. A study indicated that out of 42 mated pairs, all but one of male was larger than the female of the pair. The males were on average 11 percent heavier along with having longer wing chords.<ref name=\"Haggerty\">{{cite journal|author=Haggerty, Thomas M.|year=2006|title=Sexual size dimorphism and assortative mating in Carolina Wrens|journal=Journal of Field Ornithology|volume=77|issue=3|pages=259\u201365|url=http://www.buildingthepride.com/faculty/tmhaggerty/Articles/dimorphism%20article.pdf|doi=10.1111/j.1557-9263.2006.00051.x}}</ref> \n \nThere are several differences among the subspecies. For ''T. l. ludovicianus'', the [[crown (anatomy)|crown]] is rich brown that appears more chestnut-colored on its [[rump (animal)|rump]] and uppertail-coverts. Shoulders and greater [[covert feathers|coverts]] are a rich brown, with a series of small white dots on the lesser primary coverts. The secondary coverts are rich brown with a darker brown barring on both webs; the bars on the primaries are on the outerwebs only, but darker and more noticeable. The [[flight feathers|rectrices]] are brown with 18 to 20 bars that span across the tail. The white [[supercilium|supercilious streak]] borders thinly with a black above and below, and extends above and beyond its shoulders. The ear coverts are speckled gray and grayish-black. Its chin and throat are grey that becomes buff on its chest, flank and belly, though the latter two are of a warmer color. The underwing coverts sport a grayish buff color. Its [[iris (anatomy)|iris]] is reddish-brown, the [[upper mandible]] is lemon-colored and paler at the base and [[lower mandible]]. The legs are flesh-colored.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n\nAs for the other subspecies in contrast to ''T. l. ludovicianus'', ''T. l. berlandieri'' is of a slightly smaller build, but possesses a larger bill, the upperparts are duller brown with deeper colored underparts, ''T. l. lomitensis'' is of a duller color (than either ''ludovicianus'' or ''berlandieri'') with its underparts either pale or almost white, ''T. l. miamensis'' contains darker rusty chestnut upperparts and deeper colored below. ''T. l. burleighi'' is duller and sootier with less distinct tail markings, ''T. l. mesophilus'' has paler underparts and a whiter supercilium, and ''T. l. tropicalis'' is darker than all races, and contains heavier bars than ''T. l. berlandieri''.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n\n===Plumage===\nThe juvenile ''T.l. ludovicianus'' is similar in appearance, but the plumage is generally paler with a softer texture with buff-tipped wing coverts, a superciliary streak is less white, a fluffy vent and crissum (the undertail [[Covert feather|coverts]] surrounding the [[cloaca]]) without bars.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Bent\"/> In August and September, the partial plumage molt for the post-juvenile wrens is darker in color and affects the contour plumage, wing coverts, tail and develops a whiter superciliary stripe. The post-nuptial molt for adults in the same time period is more pronounced in color than the spring molt, with both sexes similar in appearance.<ref name=\"Bent\"/>\n\n===Life span===\n[[File:Thryothorus heads.jpg|thumb|left|285px|Sketches of ''Thryothorus ludovicianus'', ''T.l. lomitensis'', and ''Thryomanes bewickii'' (Bewick's wren) and one of its subspecies.]]\nSurvival rates differ by region. A male captured in [[Arkansas]] lived to be at least 73 months old, and in [[Alabama]], the oldest female and male captured were six and ten years old, respectively. A [[Mark and recapture|mark-and-recapture]] analysis of the wrens analyzing survival probability within the [[Southeastern United States]] captured was monitored from 1992 to 2003. Roughly 90 percent of the banded wrens died within 10 years.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/>\n\n===Similar species===\nThe easiest species to confuse with the Carolina wren is Bewick's wren,<ref name=Martinez/> which differs in being smaller but with a longer tail, grayer-brown above and whiter below. The Carolina and white-browed wrens differ from the [[house wren]] in being larger, with a decidedly longer [[beak|bill]] and hind toe; their [[Culmen (bird)|culmen]] has a notch behind the tip.<ref name=Brattstrom/>\n\n==Habitat and distribution==\nThese birds are largely resident, and will only disperse beyond their range after mild winters.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> Carolina wrens sporadically breed as far north as [[Maine]] and [[Quebec]] after mild winters.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"NatGeo\">{{cite book|last=Dunn|first=John Lloyd|last2=Alderfer|first2=Jonathan K.|title=National Geographic Illustrated Birds of North America|publisher=National Geographic Books|year=2004|page=342|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1VsvhUl1dyEC&pg=PT343|isbn=978-1426205255}}</ref> In certain parts of their range, such as most of [[Iowa]], prolonged periods of snow can curtail potential expansion.<ref name=\"Jackson\">{{cite book|last=Jackson|first=Laura Press|title=The Iowa Breeding Bird Atlas|publisher=University of Iowa Press|year=1996|pages=266\u20137|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=igp_WugmoX8C&pg=PA266|isbn=978-1426205255}}</ref> Permanent breeding locations range from eastern [[Nebraska]], southern [[Michigan]], southeast [[Ontario]] and the [[New England]] states to Mexican states such as [[Coahuila]], [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], [[San Luis Potos\u00ed]] and [[Tamaulipas]] and the [[Gulf Coast of the United States]].<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> Local occurrences with infrequent and likely breeding locations include southeast [[South Dakota]], central [[Kansas]], eastern [[Colorado]], western [[Oklahoma]] and [[Texas]] as far as [[Maine]] and [[New Brunswick]].<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> There have been occasional vagrants spotted in [[Colorado]], [[New Mexico]], and [[Arizona]], [[Wyoming]], [[South Dakota]], [[Manitoba]], [[Nova Scotia]], and the [[Gulf of St. Lawrence]].<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"NatGeo\"/>\n\n[[File:Carolina Wren (4249754138).jpg|thumb|Carolina wren at feeder]]\nThe range of the wrens increased northward and westward in several regions over the past few centuries. In [[Massachusetts]], the wrens had expanded westward and northeastward from its former southeastern location in approximately 35 years, in [[New York (state)|New York]] the population increased three-fold in roughly 25 years, while in midwest states such as [[Ohio]] and [[Michigan]] have seen numbers of the birds increase since the mid-1800s and early 1900s, respectively.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> Expansion around [[Ontario]] occurred since early reports in 1890 and 1905. Explanations given include infrequent winter storms in the 20th century, expanded forest habitats, and the wrens taking advantage of urban areas containing feeders, especially in winter.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/>\n\nCarolina wrens adapt to various habitats. Natural habitats include various types of woodland such as [[oak]] hardwoods and mixed oak-pine woodlands, [[ash tree|ash]] and [[elm tree|elmwoods]], hickory-oak woodlands with a healthy amount of tangled undergrowth.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\"/> The preferred habitats are [[riparian forest]], [[shrubland|brushy edges]], [[swamp]]s, overgrown [[farmland]], and [[suburban]] yards with abundant thick shrubs and trees, and parks.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\"/> It has an affinity for dilapidated buildings and unkempt yards in man-made areas.<ref name=\"Dunne\"/> Subspecies ''burleighi'' and ''neophilus'' inhabit [[slash pine]] and [[Sabal|palmettos]].<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\"/>\n\n==Behavior==\n\n===Song and calls===\nCarolina wrens sing year round and at any point during the daytime, with the exception of performing during the most harsh weather conditions.<ref name=\"Dunne\"/> The birds are also the only species in the family [[Certhiidae]] that neither sings in duet nor has their song control regions affect repertoire size.<ref name=\"Nealen00\">{{cite journal|author1=Nealen, Paul M. |author2=Perkel, David J. |year=2000|title=Sexual Dimorphism in the Song System of the Carolina Wren (''Thryothorus ludovicianus'')|journal=The Journal of Comparative Neurology|volume=418|issue=4|pages=346\u2013360|pmid=10701831|doi=10.1002/(sici)1096-9861(20000313)418:3<346::aid-cne8>3.3.co;2-b }}</ref> Males alone sing, and have a repertoire of at least twenty different phrase patterns and on average, thirty two.<ref name=\"Nealen00\"/><ref name=\"Elliott2\">{{cite book|last=Elliott|first=Lang|title=Music of the Birds: A Celebration of Bird Song|publisher= Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|year=1999|page=[https://archive.org/details/musicofbirdscele0000elli/page/30 30]|url=https://archive.org/details/musicofbirdscele0000elli|url-access=registration|isbn=978-0618006977}}</ref> One of these patterns is repeated for several minutes, and although the male's song can be repeated up to twelve times, the general number of songs range from three to five times in repetition. While singing, the tail of the birds is pointed downward. Some general vocalizations have been transcribed as ''teakettle-teakettle-teakettle'' and ''cheery-cheery-cheery''.<ref name=\"Bent\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\"/> Various descriptions of the ''teakettle'' song include ''whee-udel, whee-udel, whee-udel'', ''che-wortel, che-wortel'' and ''t\u00fartee-t\u00fartee-t\u00fartee'' and familiar names and phrases such as ''sweet heart, sweet heart'', ''come to me, come to me'', ''sweet William'', and ''Richelieu, Richelieu''.<ref name=\"Bent\"/>\n\nMales are capable of increasing their repertoire through song learning, but due to their sedentary nature and territorial defense habits, the song learning must occur within the first three months of life.<ref name=\"Morton87\"/> Geographic barriers affect song repertoire size from male wrens, as one study indicated that distances separated as close as {{convert|3|km}} by water barriers can have the same effect as that of a distance of {{convert|145|km}} in the mainland with no barriers.<ref name=\"Morton87\">{{cite journal|author=Morton, Eugene S.|year=2005|title=The Effects of Distance and Isolation on Song-type Sharing in the Carolina Wren|journal=Wilson Bulletin|volume=99|issue=4|pages=601\u201310|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v099n04/p0601-p0610.pdf|doi=}}</ref>\n\nFemale Carolina wrens possess song control regions that would appear to make them capable of singing with repertoires like the male. Due to vocalizations that they occasionally make with the male, it has been suggested that song perception plays a role and is of behavioral relevance.<ref name=\"Nealen00\"/>\n\n[[File:Carolina Wren (7318066894).jpg|thumb|left|Carolina wren on Rutland Township Forest Preserve]]\nDifferent subspecies have variations in songs and calls, such as ''miamensis'' having a more rapid song that contains more notes than the races that are further north.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n\nTheir songs can be confused with the [[Kentucky warbler]]. The song patterns are similar, but is of a different quality, as the warbler's songs is described as richer, with more ringing and a hurried pace.<ref name=\"Dunne\"/> Other bird species that have their songs described as akin to the wrens are the [[Colaptes|flicker]], [[Baltimore oriole]], [[grey catbird]], and more specifically the ''peto, peto, peto'' calls of the [[tufted titmouse]], and whistles of the [[northern cardinal]].<ref name=\"Bent\"/> Occasionally, the wrens mimic other species; in [[Pennsylvania]] this trait has caused the bird also to be known as the 'mocking wren'.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n\n===Sexual selection===\nA 2006 study suggested that the correlation of tail length and body size in males, wing length in females, and lifespan for both sexes were signs of individual quality, and the wrens of high quality tend to mate with like individuals. The courting and antagonistic encounters that involve the tail fanning and wing drooping was suggested to be a possible signaling use. Age and life experience are not thought of as significant for potential mates due to their relatively short lifespan and sedentary lifestyle. Due to the large size of male wrens and the male's vigor in defending its territory, intrasexual selection was given as a possible explanation for the sexual dimorphism.<ref name=\"Haggerty\"/>\n\n===Territorial and predator defense===\nBoth sexes are involved in defending the territory. One aspect of territorial defense involves identifying the proximity of the threat based on the loudness of bird song as well as the level of degradation of the calls. In experiments involving playback, the wrens are capable of discriminating between degraded and undegraded songs, as well as degraded songs in the same acoustic conditions, and can detect changes of acoustic properties within their territories, such as songs under foliage.<ref name=\"Naguib95\">{{cite journal|author=Naguib, Marc|year=1995|title=Ranging by Song in Carolina Wrens (''Thryothorus ludovicianus''): Effects of Environmental Acoustics and Strength of Song Degradation|journal=Behaviour|volume=133|issue=7|pages=541\u2013559|url=http://www.unc.edu/home/rhwiley/pdfs/EnvironAcousticsCW.pdf|doi=10.1163/156853996x00206}}</ref> Song degradation can also be used to determine the proximity of potential intruders. If the song of a bird appears to be degraded, the wrens will assume that the threat is distant and not respond; if the song is not degraded, they respond by attacking.<ref name=\"Richards\">{{cite journal|author=Richards, Douglas G.|year=1981|title=Estimation of the Distance of Singing Conspecifics by the Carolina Wren|journal=The Auk|volume=98|issue=1|pages=127\u201333|url=http://www.unc.edu/home/rhwiley/pdfs/Richards1981Distance.pdf|jstor=4085615}}</ref> Not all birds within their territory are potential enemies. Some species of birds that are neighbors are designated as 'dear-enemies' by the wrens, and the responses to neighbors and intruders in their territories differ by the season. In spring, the wrens respond more aggressively toward neighbors, though in the fall, no major discrepancy in responses is shown.<ref name=\"Hyman\">{{cite journal|author=Hyman, Jeremy|year=2005|title=Seasonal Variation in Response to Neighbors and Strangers by a Territorial Songbird|journal=Ethology|volume=111|issue=10|pages=951\u201361|url=http://www.unc.edu/~rhwiley/pdfs/Hyman2005.pdf|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2005.01104.x}}</ref> When protecting their nest, alarm calls are the general response. The wrens judge the size of the potential threat, such as a [[blue jay]] and avoid the risk of injury when attacking.<ref name=\"D'Orazio\">{{cite journal|author1=D'Orazio, Kelly |author2=Neudorf, Diane L. H. |year=2008|title=Nest Defense by Carolina Wrens|journal=The Wilson Journal of Ornithology|volume=120|issue=3|pages=467\u201372|jstor=20456180|doi=10.1676/06-149.1 }}</ref> Countersinging produced by intruder birds is more likely to be taken as an aggressive threat to male Carolina wrens.<ref name=\"Hyman2\">{{cite journal|author=Hyman, Jeremy|year=2003|title=Countersinging as a signal of aggression in a territorial songbird|journal=Animal Behaviour|volume=65|issue=6|pages=1179\u201385|url=http://www.unc.edu/home/rhwiley/pdfs/Hyman1.pdf|doi=10.1006/anbe.2003.2175}}</ref>\n\nBoth males and females utilize calls in alarm situations, especially in territorial disputes and encounters with predators. Males alone produce the ''cheer'' call, which can sound indistinct. In southern regions of their range, the sound males use in alarm disputes is a ringing ''pink'' or ''p'dink'' sound. Females are the only ones that can perform the paired ''dit-dit'' or chatter sounds. The former can be used in territorial disputes with predators, and with at least northern populations the songs are used in alternation with the males ''cheer'' chant. The chatter is used exclusively with territorial encounters with male song, and the song can either follow or overlap her mate's song.<ref name=\"Nealen00\"/><ref name=\"Elliott\">{{cite book|last=Elliott|first=Lang|title=Know Your Bird Sounds: Songs and calls of yard, garden, and city birds|publisher=Stackpole Books|year=2004|page=29|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ChyiBZr6GU8C&pg=PA28|isbn=978-0811729635}}</ref>\n\n===Feeding===\nCarolina wrens spend the majority of their time on or near the ground searching for food, or in tangles of vegetation and vines. They also probe bark crevices on lower tree levels, or pick up leaf-litter in order to search for prey. Their diet consists of invertebrates, such as [[beetles]], [[Hemiptera|true bugs]], [[grasshopper]]s, [[katydid]]s, [[spider]]s, [[ant]]s, [[bee]]s, and [[wasp]]s. Small [[lizard]]s and [[tree frog]]s also make up the carnivorous portion of their diet. Vegetable matter makes up a small percentage of their diets, such as fruit pulp and various [[seed]]s. In the northern portion of their range, they frequent [[bird feeder]]s.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\"/>\n\n===Movement===\nCarolina wrens are wary, and are more often heard than seen. When on the ground, they move in jerky hops pillaging through various objects, whether man-made or natural.<ref name=\"Dunne\"/> While moving abruptly, they pause momentarily for chattering or singing.<ref name=\"Bent\">{{cite journal|author=Bent, Arthur C.|year=1948|title=Life Histories of North American Nuthatches, Wrens, Thrashers, and their Allies: Order Passeriformes|journal=Bulletin of the United States National Museum|volume=|issue=195|pages=205\u201316|doi=10.5479/si.03629236.195.1|hdl=10088/10012|hdl-access=free}}</ref>  When stationary, they move in twitched motions, jerking their breast around.<ref name=\"Dunne\"/> They also sun- or sand-bathe.<ref name=\"Hauser\">{{cite journal|author=Hauser, Doris C.|year=1957|title=Some Obversations of Sun-bathing in Birds|journal=The Wilson Bulletin|volume=69|issue=1|pages=259\u201365|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v069n01/p0078-p0090.pdf|doi=}}</ref> The wrens also displays a skittish behavior when encountered by [[human]]s, as they can be seen thrusting off into cover slowly if approaching is detected. However, they occasionally seek out humans that are near, so long as there is no movement from them.<ref name=\"Bent\"/> Other movements involve being capable of crawling like a [[Treecreeper|creeper]] and hanging upside-down like a [[nuthatch]].<ref name=\"Dunne\"/>\n\nFlights are generally of short duration, rapid, low-leveled, and wavelike. The wings during flight are flapped rapidly, and are frequently used during foraging. They are also capable of flying vertically from the base of a tree to the top in a single wing assisted bound.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\">{{cite book|last=Dunne|first=Pete|title=Pete Dunne's Essential Field Guide Companion: A Comprehensive Resource for Identifying North American Birds|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|year=2006|page=479|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ISgKT2ehj7oC&pg=PA511|isbn=978-0-300-09059-8}}</ref>\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Carolina Wren nesting in a duck box - Flickr - Andrea Westmoreland.jpg|thumb|Carolina wren nesting in a duck nestbox.]]\nCarolina wrens are both genetically and socially [[monogamy|monogamous]] and will usually mate for life.  Mate changing is rare,<ref name=\"Haggerty\"/> and there has been one possible observation of polygamy.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> During the winter season, males are more responsible for guarding the territory. Females vary in succeeding to maintain winter territories without a mate.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> It has been suggested that the possibility of desertion and decline in care-taking from males along with the need for security in resources year-round prevent extra pair copulations from females, as the mortality rate for Carolina wrens peaks during the winter.<ref name=\"Haggerty&Morton\">{{cite journal|author1=Haggerty, Thomas M. |author2=Morton, Eugene M. |author3=Fleischer, Robert C. |year=2001|title=Genetic Monogamy in Carolina Wrens (''Thryothorus ludovicianus'')|jstor=4089770|journal=The Auk|volume=118|issue=1|pages=215\u201319|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v118n01/p00215-p00219.pdf|doi=10.1093/auk/118.1.215}}</ref> Along with thermoregulatory benefits, [[Bird#Resting and roosting|roosting]] is thought to reinforce pair-bonding and prevent divorce between mates.<ref name=\"Labinsky\">{{cite journal|author1=Labinsky, Ronald F. |author2=Arnett Jr., John E. |year=2006|title=Pair Roosting of Carolina Wrens (''Thryothorus ludovicianus'')|journal=The Wilson Journal of Ornithology|volume=118|issue=4|pages=566\u2013569|url=|doi=10.1676/05-109.1|jstor=20455927}}</ref>\n\nThe nests are arch-shaped structures with a side entrance and built of dried plants or strips of bark, as well as horsehair, string, wool and snake sloughs. Males obtain nesting materials while the females remains at the site to construct the nest. Nests are located in fragmented or complete cavities in trees, or in man-made structures such as bird-boxes, buildings, tin cans, mailboxes or unorthodox places such as pockets of hanging jackets in sheds or in a [[tractor]] in everyday use.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Bent\"/> Nests are from {{convert|1|-|3|m|ft|abbr=on}} from the ground and are rarely higher. They occasionally can be built in sloping locations or at ground level.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n\nEgg laying dates and clutch size vary by region; in Texas the time period is from late February to late August, in Iowa it ranges from late April to June.<ref name=\"TAMU\">{{cite web|title=''Thryothorus ludovicianus''|url=http://txtbba.tamu.edu/species-accounts/carolina-wren/|year=2006|work=Texas A&M AgriLifeExtension|publisher=Texas A&M University|accessdate=31 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Jackson\"/> The clutch size is generally 3 to 6 eggs, but can reach as high as seven in Texas.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"TAMU\"/> The eggs are creamy white with brown or reddish-brown spots, and are more heavily marked at the broad end.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> The eggs are incubated by the female for 12\u201316 days. After the young hatch, they are fed exclusively on invertebrates and they fledge in 12\u201314 days. As many as three broods may be raised by a pair in a single breeding season.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> In one study, three of the 70 fledglings remained or defended territory adjacent to the natal area.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/>\n\nMale and females are involved in the process of provisioning at similar rates throughout most nest stages, with the males providing slightly more in the nestling stages. Both sexes increase their provision rates as the nestlings grow in age.<ref name=\"Neudorf\">{{cite journal|author1=Neudorf, Diane L. H. |author2=Broddick, Mallory J. |author3=Cureton II |author4=James C. |year=2013|title=Parental Provisioning by Carolina Wrens|journal=The Wilson Journal of Ornithology|volume=125|issue=1|pages=179\u2013184|url=|doi=10.1676/12-009.1}}</ref>\n\n==Predation and threats==\n[[Brood parasitism]] by the [[brown-headed cowbird]] is common, with up to 25% of Carolina wren nests being affected in certain regions such as [[Oklahoma]] and [[Alabama]].<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> Cowbird parasitism peaks in April at 41%, and is as low as 8% and 0% in July and August, respectively. Female cowbirds sometimes eject Carolina wren eggs before laying their own, and even if host eggs are retained, the size of cowbird eggs negatively affect the hatching success of wren eggs. As a result, cowbirds may have a significant impact on the reproductive success of wrens.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> The feeding rate for cowbird nestlings is higher than wren feeding rates, and some have been raised to independence.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> This also can be detrimental to the survival of wren nestlings.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> A rare instance of brood-parasitism by a [[house finch]] has been recorded.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|journal=The Wilson Journal of Ornithology|volume= 118|issue=3|pages=413\u2013415|year=2006|doi=10.1676/05-102.1 |title=Carolina Wren Nest Successfully Parasitized by House Finch |author1=Wood, Douglas R.  |author2=William A. Carter}}</ref> The rate of brood parasitism is thought to be lower in more natural and concealed nesting locations.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> Body parasites such as the larvae of [[blowflies]] feed on nestlings and the blood loss weakens nestlings.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\">{{cite web|url=http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/bna/species/188/articles/introduction|title=The Birds of North America Online: Carolina Wren}}</ref> Fellow species of wren such as Bewick's wren and the [[winter wren]] compete for nesting locations and food, respectively.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/>\n\nIn [[Virginia]], some Carolina wrens populations show high levels of [[mercury (element)|mercury]] in their blood and this is acquired from feeding all-year-round on spiders.<ref name=\"JacksonEvers\"/>{{#tag:ref|The [[Holston River|North Folk Holston]] and [[Shenandoah River#South Fork Shenandoah River|South River]]s were used in the study and were both contaminated by industrial activity.|group=\"note\"}} Spiders being at a higher [[trophic level]]s contain a higher concentrations of mercury (through [[biomagnification]]) than herbivorous invertebrates. As these wrens are year-round residents, they are at a higher risk than other species to acquire mercury in its blood. Nest abandonment and failure to raise young were more common with higher mercury content.<ref name=\"JacksonEvers\">{{cite journal|author1=Jackson, Alison K. |author2=Evers, David C. |author3=Etterson, Matthew A. |author4=Condon, Anne M. |author5=Folsom, Sarah B. |author6=Detweiler, Jennifer |author7=Schmerfeld, John |author8=Cristol, Daniel A. |year=2011|title=Mercury Exposure Affects the Reproductive Success of a Free-Living Terrestrial Songbird, The Carolina Wren (''Thryothorus ludovicianus'')|journal=The Auk|volume=128|issue=4|pages=759\u2013769|doi=10.1525/auk.2011.11106}}</ref> Exposure, and prolonged periods of cold, ice, and snow is thought to affect the wren nestling and adult populations, respectively.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> Wrens that outlast those winters reside in sheltered areas during the season.<ref name=\"Bent\"/>\n\nAmong the top predators of adult Carolina wrens are [[Cat predation on wildlife|domestic cats]], and snakes such as the [[timber rattlesnake]].<ref name=\"VJoS\">{{cite journal|author1=Mitchell, Joseph C. |author2=Beck, Ruth A. |year=1992|title=Free-Ranging Domestic Cat Predation on Native Vertebrates in Rural and Native Virginia|journal=Virginia Journal of Science|volume=43|issue=1B|pages=197\u2013208|url=http://www.vacadsci.org/vjsArchives/V43/43-1B/43-197.pdf|doi=}}</ref><ref name=\"GJoS\">{{cite journal|author1=Parmley, Dennis |author2=Parmley, Amanda M. |year=2001 |title=Food Habits of the Canebrake Rattlesnake (''Crotalus horridus atricaudatus'') in Central Georgia |journal=Georgia Journal of Science |volume=59 |issue=4 |pages=172\u201380 |url=http://facstaff.gpc.edu/~jaliff/GA%20Sci%2059-4.pdf#page=16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014054644/http://facstaff.gpc.edu/~jaliff/GA%20Sci%2059-4.pdf |archivedate=2013-10-14 }}</ref> [[Raccoon]]s and [[black rat snake]]s also feed on wren eggs and nestlings.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/>\n\n==In culture==\n[[File:2000 SC Proof.png|thumb|right|140px|South Carolina state quarter]]\nIn 1930, the South Carolina Federated Women's club adopted the Carolina wren as the unofficial state bird over the [[Mourning dove|eastern mourning dove]] and pushed for its official state adoption until 1939, when the South Carolina Legislature named the [[northern mockingbird]] as the state bird. In 1948, the legislature repealed their previous decision, and the wren became the official state bird.<ref name=\"SouthCarolina\">{{cite web|title=South Carolina State Bird \u2013 Thryrothorus ludovicianus|url=http://www.netstate.com/states/symb/birds/sc_carolina_wren.htm|website=|publisher=NetState|accessdate=31 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, the Carolina wren was featured on the back of the South Carolina edition of the [[50 State Quarters]].<ref name=\"TheUS50\">{{cite web|title=The Official South Carolina State Quarter|url=http://www.theus50.com/southcarolina/quarter.php|website=|publisher=TheUS50|accessdate=31 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|1|group=note}}\n\n==References==<!-- WilsonBull18:47 (compare to current Ohio checklist http://www.ohiobirds.org/publications/OBRClist.pdf) -->\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Brattstrom>{{cite journal|author1=Brattstrom, Bayard H.  |author2=Howell, Thomas R. |year=1956|title= The Birds of the Revilla Gigedo Islands, Mexico|journal=[[Condor (journal)|Condor]]|volume=58|issue=2|pages= 107\u2013120|doi=10.2307/1364977|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v058n02/p0107-p0120.pdf|jstor=1364977 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=David>{{cite journal|author1=David, Normand |author2=Dubois, Alain |year=2011|title= The original spellings of ''Thryothorus'' Vieillot, 1816 (Vertebrata, Aves): a correction|url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2011/f/z02918p068f.pdf |journal=[[Zootaxa]]|volume= 2918|pages= 68|doi=10.11646/zootaxa.2918.1.6 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Mann>{{cite journal|author1=Mann, Nigel I.|author2=Barker, F. Keith|author3=Graves, Jeff A.|author4=Dingess-Mann, Kimberly A.|author5=Slater, Peter J.B.|title=Molecular data delineate four genera of ''\"Thryothorus\"'' wrens|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.014|url=http://www.tc.umn.edu/~barke042/pdfs/Mann.et.al06.pdf|year=2006|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=750\u20139|pmid=16750640|access-date=2007-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071202114315/http://www.tc.umn.edu/~barke042/pdfs/Mann.et.al06.pdf#|archive-date=2007-12-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Martinez>{{cite journal|author1=Mart\u00ednez G\u00f3mez |author2=Juan E. |author3=Barber, Bruian R. |author4=Peterson, A. Townsend |title=Phylogenetic position and generic placement of the Socorro Wren (''Thryomanes sissonii'') |doi=10.1642/0004-8038(2005)122[0050:PPAGPO]2.0.CO;2 |url=http://www.specifysoftware.org/Informatics/bios/biostownpeterson/MBP_A_2005.pdf |year=2005 |volume=122 |pages=50 |journal=The Auk |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217114932/http://www.specifysoftware.org/Informatics/bios/biostownpeterson/MBP_A_2005.pdf |archivedate=2008-12-17 |hdl=1808/16612 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Thryothorus ludovicianus|the Carolina wren}}\n{{Wikispecies|Thryothorus ludovicianus}}\n*[http://www.mbr-pwrc.usgs.gov/id/framlst/i7180id.html Identification tips] \u2013 USGS Patuxent Bird Identification InfoCenter\n*[http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/BirdGuide/Carolina_Wren.html Species account] \u2013 Cornell Lab of Ornithology\n*[http://www.birdhouses101.com/carolina-wren.asp About] \u2013 Bird Houses 101\n*[http://www.bird-stamps.org/cspecies/13504200.htm Stamps] \u2013 BirdLife International\n* {{InternetBirdCollection|carolina-wren-thryothorus-ludovicianus|Carolina wren}}\n* {{VIREO|Carolina+Wren|Carolina wren}}\n* [http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/index.php/download_file/view/1296/724/ Sound] \u2013 Florida Museum of Natural History\n\n<!-- see the decent RangeMap at: \"www.natureserve.org\" ....only \"Permanent Resident\" on map-NOTE ( (2) small \"Spots\" of Perm Resident in \"Nicaragua\")-->\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1585636}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:wren, Carolina}}\n[[Category:Thryothorus|Carolina wren]]\n[[Category:Native birds of Eastern Canada]]\n[[Category:Native birds of the Eastern United States]]\n[[Category:Birds of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1790|Carolina wren]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by John Latham (ornithologist)|Carolina wren]]\n", "text_old": "{{Good article}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Carolina wren\n| image = Carolina Wren1.jpg\n| image2 = Thryothorus ludovicianus song.ogg\n| image2_caption = Recorded in [[Cape May, New Jersey]], US\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22711450/0 |title=''Thryothorus ludovicianus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Thryothorus\n| parent_authority = [[Louis Jean Pierre Vieillot|Vieillot]], 1816<ref name=David/>\n| species = ludovicianus\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1790)\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision_ref = <ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n| subdivision = {{collapsible list|bullets = true|title=<small>List</small>\n|''T. l. berlandieri''\n|''T. l. burleighi''\n|''T. l. lomitensis''\n|''T. l. ludovicianus''\n|''T. l. miamensis''\n|''T. l. nesophilus''\n|''T. l. tropicalis''\n|''T. (l.) albinucha'' \u2013 White-browed wren}}\n| range_map = Thryothorus ludovicianus species distribution map.svg\n| range_map_caption = Range of the Carolina wren (''T. ludovicianus'')\n| synonyms = ''Sylvia ludoviciana'' <small>(Latham, 1790)</small>\n| synonyms_ref = <ref>{{cite book|title=Check-list of birds of the World. Volume IX.|editor=Mayr, E.|editor2=Greenway, J.C. Jr.|year=1960|publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology|place=Cambridge, Mass. |url=https://archive.org/stream/checklistofbirds91960pete#page/408/mode/2up|pages=409\u2013410}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Carolina wren''' (''Thryothorus ludovicianus'') is a common [[species]] of [[wren]] that is a resident in the eastern half of the [[United States|United States of America]], the extreme south of [[Ontario]], Canada, and the extreme northeast of [[Mexico]]. Severe winters restrict the northern limits of their range while favorable weather conditions lead to a northward extension of their breeding range. Their preferred habitat is in dense cover in forests, farm edges and suburban areas. This wren is the [[List of U.S. state birds|state bird]] of [[South Carolina]].\n\nThere are seven recognized subspecies across the range of these wrens and they differ slightly in song and appearance. The birds are generally inconspicuous, avoiding the open for extended periods of time. When out in the open, they investigate their surroundings and are rarely stationary. After finding a mate, pairs maintain a [[territory (animal)|territory]] and stay together for several years. Both sexes give out alarm calls, but only males sing to advertise territory. Carolina wrens raise multiple broods during the summer breeding season, but can fall victim to [[brood parasitism]] by [[brown-headed cowbird]]s, among other species. Some populations have been affected by mercury contamination.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe Carolina wren was first described under the name of ''Sylvia ludoviciana'' by [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] in 1790.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>{{#tag:ref|Johann Friedrich Gmelin wrongly associated the Carolina wren with the European wrens under the name ''Motacilla troglodytes'' (originally coined by [[Carl Linnaeus]] in [[Systema Naturae]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Linnaeus|first=C.|authorlink=Carl Linnaeus|title=Systema Naturae per Regna Tria Naturae, Secundum Classes, Ordines, Genera, Species, cum Characteribus, Differentiis, Synonymis, Locis. Tomus I. Editio Decima, Reformata|volume=v.1| publisher=Laurentius Salvius|location=[[Stockholm|Holmiae]]|language=Latin| year=1758|page=188|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/727076#page/208/mode/1up}}</ref> in 1788.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Harding|first=J.|title=Journal of the Academy of the Sciences of Philadelphia: Volume IV, Part I| publisher=[[Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University|Academy of Sciences of Philadelphia]]|location=[[Philadelphia]]|year=1824|pages=28\u201329|url=https://archive.org/stream/journalofacademy04acaduoft#page/28/mode/2up}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} [[Louis Jean Pierre Vieillot]] considered all wrens under the genus [[Troglodytes (bird)|''Troglodytes'']] and called the Carolina wren ''Troglodytes arundinaceus'' but placed it subsequently in a separate genus ''Thryothorus'' (initially misspelled ''Thriothorus''\n<ref name=David />) that he created in 1816.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Auk|title=A synopsis of the genus commonly called Anorthura|author=Oberholser, Harry C.|year=1902|pages=175\u2013181|url=https://archive.org/stream/jstor-4069309/4069309#page/n1/mode/2up|jstor=4069309|volume=19|issue=2|doi=10.2307/4069309}}</ref> ''Thryothorus'' is of [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] origin from the combination of ''thryon'' (rush, reed) and ''thouros'' (derivative of verb ''throskein'' to leap up, spring, jump at) which means 'reed jumper'; its [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] ''ludovicianus'' is a post-classical [[Latin]] term for ''Ludovicus'' (derivative from [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]]) that means 'of [[Louisiana (New France)|Louisiana]]' that identifies the locality of the specimen collected near [[New Orleans]].<ref name=\"Sandrock\">{{cite book|last=Sandrock|first=James|title=The Scientific Nomenclature of Birds in the Upper Midwest|publisher=University of Iowa Press|year=2014|page=144|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_I3zAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA144|isbn=978-1609382254}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/coueschecklistof00couerich#page/31/mode/1up|page=31|title=Coues check list of North American Birds|edition=2nd|year=1882|author=Coues, Elliot|publisher=Estes and Lauriat|place=Boston}}</ref>\n\nThere are seven recognized subspecies of the Carolina wren:<ref name=\"Brewer15\">{{cite book|last=Brewer|first=David|title=Wrens, Dippers, and Thrashers|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2001|pages=132\u20134|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-r35SXfm9BYC&pg=PA134|isbn=978-0-300-09059-8}}</ref><ref name=\"Carolina or White-browed Wren\">{{cite web|title=Carolina or White-browed Wren (Thryothorus [ludovicianus or albinucha])|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=CB5469E1211E7EFF|publisher=AviBase|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n*''T. l. ludovicianus'' (Latham, 1790) \u2013 Southeast Canada (Southern Ontario, irregularly in Eastern and Southern Quebec) and the eastern United States (Southern [[Wisconsin]] and [[New England]] southward to [[Texas]] and northern [[Florida]]).\n*''T. l. miamensis'' '''Florida wren''' (Ridgway, 1875) \u2013 Florida from approximately 30 degrees ([[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]]) region southward through the rest of the state.\n*''T. l. nesophilus'' (Stevenson, 1973) \u2013 [[Dog Island (Florida)|Dog Island]] in Northwestern Florida.\n*''T. l. burleighi'' \u2013 '''Burleigh's Carolina wren''' (Lowery, 1940) Offshore islands off of the [[Mississippi]] coast: [[Cat Island (Mississippi)|Cat Island]], [[Ship Island (Mississippi)]], and [[Horn Island (Mississippi)|Horn Island]].\n*''T. l. lomitensis'' \u2013 '''Lomita wren''' (Sennett, 1890) southern Texas to the extreme northeast of Mexico ([[Tamaulipas]]).\n*''T. l. berlandieri'' \u2013 '''Berlandier's wren''' (S. F. Baird, 1858) Northeastern Mexico (eastern [[Coahuila]], [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], and southwestern Tamaulipas)\n*''T. l. tropicalis'' \u2013 Northeastern Mexico (eastern [[San Luis Potos\u00ed]] and southern Tamaulipas).\n*''T. ludovicianus'' is traditionally placed within its own genus as its only representative of North America, but recent DNA work suggests it is closely allied with the [[Bewick's wren]].<ref name=Mann/> A distinct population in the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] of Mexico, [[Belize]], [[Nicaragua]], and in [[Guatemala]] is treated as a separate species, either known as Cabot's wren or white-browed wren (''Thryothorus albinucha'').<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"TAMU\"/> It is considered a subspecies of ''T. ludovicianus'' by some authors, however.<ref name=\"Carolina or White-browed Wren\"/>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:95%; line-height:95%\n|1={{clade\n |1={{clade\n  |1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Grey-barred wren|Campylorhynchus megalopterus]]''\n   |2=''[[Cactus wren|Campylorhynchus brunneicapillus]]'' }}\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=''[[Bewick's wren|Thryomanes bewicki]]''\n   |2={{clade\n    |1='''''Thryothorus ludovicianus ludovicianus'''''\n    |2='''''T. l. albinucha''''' }} }} }}\n |2={{clade\n  |1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Peruvian wren|Cinnycerthia peruana]]''\n   |2={{clade\n    |1=''[[Fawn-breasted wren|Thryothorus guarayanus]]''\n    |2=''[[Buff-breasted wren|Thryothorus leucotis]]'' }} }}\n  |2={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n    |1={{clade\n     |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n       |1=''[[White-breasted wood wren|Henicorhina leucosticta]]''\n       |2=''[[Grey-breasted wood wren|Henicorhina leucophrys]]'' }}\n      |2=''[[White-bellied wren|Uropsila leucogastra]]'' }}\n     |2=''[[Musician wren|Cyphorhinus arada]]'' }}\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Spot-breasted wren|Thryothorus maculipectus]]''\n     |2=''[[Coraya wren|Thryothorus coraya]]'' }} }}\n   |2=''[[Sinaloa wren|Thryothorus sinaloa]]'' }} }} }} }}\n\n==Description==\n[[File:CarolinaWren-23SEP2016.jpg|alt=Carolina Wren|left|thumb|335x335px|Carolina Wren in [[Greenville, South Carolina]]. ]]\nAt {{convert|12.5|to|14|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, with a {{convert|29|cm|in|abbr=on}} wingspan and a weight of about {{convert|18|to|23|g|oz|abbr=on}}, the Carolina wren is a fairly large wren; the second largest in the United States species after the [[cactus wren]]. Among standard measurements, the [[Wing chord (biology)|wing chord]] is {{convert|5.4|to|6.4|cm|in|abbr=on}}, the [[tail]] is {{convert|4.5|to|5.6|cm|in|abbr=on}}, the [[Culmen (bird)|culmen]] is {{convert|1.4|to|1.8|cm|in|abbr=on}} and the [[Tarsus (skeleton)|tarsus]] is {{convert|2|to|2.3|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> [[Sexual dimorphism]] is slight with males being larger than their mates. A study indicated that out of 42 mated pairs, all but one of male was larger than the female of the pair. The males were on average 11 percent heavier along with having longer wing chords.<ref name=\"Haggerty\">{{cite journal|author=Haggerty, Thomas M.|year=2006|title=Sexual size dimorphism and assortative mating in Carolina Wrens|journal=Journal of Field Ornithology|volume=77|issue=3|pages=259\u201365|url=http://www.buildingthepride.com/faculty/tmhaggerty/Articles/dimorphism%20article.pdf|doi=10.1111/j.1557-9263.2006.00051.x}}</ref> \n \nThere are several differences among the subspecies. For ''T. l. ludovicianus'', the [[crown (anatomy)|crown]] is rich brown that appears more chestnut-colored on its [[rump (animal)|rump]] and uppertail-coverts. Shoulders and greater [[covert feathers|coverts]] are a rich brown, with a series of small white dots on the lesser primary coverts. The secondary coverts are rich brown with a darker brown barring on both webs; the bars on the primaries are on the outerwebs only, but darker and more noticeable. The [[flight feathers|rectrices]] are brown with 18 to 20 bars that span across the tail. The white [[supercilium|supercilious streak]] borders thinly with a black above and below, and extends above and beyond its shoulders. The ear coverts are speckled gray and grayish-black. Its chin and throat are grey that becomes buff on its chest, flank and belly, though the latter two are of a warmer color. The underwing coverts sport a grayish buff color. Its [[iris (anatomy)|iris]] is reddish-brown, the [[upper mandible]] is lemon-colored and paler at the base and [[lower mandible]]. The legs are flesh-colored.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n\nAs for the other subspecies in contrast to ''T. l. ludovicianus'', ''T. l. berlandieri'' is of a slightly smaller build, but possesses a larger bill, the upperparts are duller brown with deeper colored underparts, ''T. l. lomitensis'' is of a duller color (than either ''ludovicianus'' or ''berlandieri'') with its underparts either pale or almost white, ''T. l. miamensis'' contains darker rusty chestnut upperparts and deeper colored below. ''T. l. burleighi'' is duller and sootier with less distinct tail markings, ''T. l. mesophilus'' has paler underparts and a whiter supercilium, and ''T. l. tropicalis'' is darker than all races, and contains heavier bars than ''T. l. berlandieri''.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n\n===Plumage===\nThe juvenile ''T.l. ludovicianus'' is similar in appearance, but the plumage is generally paler with a softer texture with buff-tipped wing coverts, a superciliary streak is less white, a fluffy vent and crissum (the undertail [[Covert feather|coverts]] surrounding the [[cloaca]]) without bars.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Bent\"/> In August and September, the partial plumage molt for the post-juvenile wrens is darker in color and affects the contour plumage, wing coverts, tail and develops a whiter superciliary stripe. The post-nuptial molt for adults in the same time period is more pronounced in color than the spring molt, with both sexes similar in appearance.<ref name=\"Bent\"/>\n\n===Life span===\n[[File:Thryothorus heads.jpg|thumb|left|285px|Sketches of ''Thryothorus ludovicianus'', ''T.l. lomitensis'', and ''Thryomanes bewickii'' (Bewick's wren) and one of its subspecies.]]\nSurvival rates differ by region. A male captured in [[Arkansas]] lived to be at least 73 months old, and in [[Alabama]], the oldest female and male captured were six and ten years old, respectively. A [[Mark and recapture|mark-and-recapture]] analysis of the wrens analyzing survival probability within the [[Southeastern United States]] captured was monitored from 1992 to 2003. Roughly 90 percent of the banded wrens died within 10 years.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/>\n\n===Similar species===\nThe easiest species to confuse with the Carolina wren is Bewick's wren,<ref name=Martinez/> which differs in being smaller but with a longer tail, grayer-brown above and whiter below. The Carolina and white-browed wrens differ from the [[house wren]] in being larger, with a decidedly longer [[beak|bill]] and hind toe; their [[Culmen (bird)|culmen]] has a notch behind the tip.<ref name=Brattstrom/>\n\n==Habitat and distribution==\nThese birds are largely resident, and will only disperse beyond their range after mild winters.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> Carolina wrens sporadically breed as far north as [[Maine]] and [[Quebec]] after mild winters.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"NatGeo\">{{cite book|last=Dunn|first=John Lloyd|last2=Alderfer|first2=Jonathan K.|title=National Geographic Illustrated Birds of North America|publisher=National Geographic Books|year=2004|page=342|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1VsvhUl1dyEC&pg=PT343|isbn=978-1426205255}}</ref> In certain parts of their range, such as most of [[Iowa]], prolonged periods of snow can curtail potential expansion.<ref name=\"Jackson\">{{cite book|last=Jackson|first=Laura Press|title=The Iowa Breeding Bird Atlas|publisher=University of Iowa Press|year=1996|pages=266\u20137|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=igp_WugmoX8C&pg=PA266|isbn=978-1426205255}}</ref> Permanent breeding locations range from eastern [[Nebraska]], southern [[Michigan]], southeast [[Ontario]] and the [[New England]] states to Mexican states such as [[Coahuila]], [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], [[San Luis Potos\u00ed]] and [[Tamaulipas]] and the [[Gulf Coast of the United States]].<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> Local occurrences with infrequent and likely breeding locations include southeast [[South Dakota]], central [[Kansas]], eastern [[Colorado]], western [[Oklahoma]] and [[Texas]] as far as [[Maine]] and [[New Brunswick]].<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> There have been occasional vagrants spotted in [[Colorado]], [[New Mexico]], and [[Arizona]], [[Wyoming]], [[South Dakota]], [[Manitoba]], [[Nova Scotia]], and the [[Gulf of St. Lawrence]].<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"NatGeo\"/>\n\n[[File:Carolina Wren (4249754138).jpg|thumb|Carolina wren at feeder]]\nThe range of the wrens increased northward and westward in several regions over the past few centuries. In [[Massachusetts]], the wrens had expanded westward and northeastward from its former southeastern location in approximately 35 years, in [[New York (state)|New York]] the population increased three-fold in roughly 25 years, while in midwest states such as [[Ohio]] and [[Michigan]] have seen numbers of the birds increase since the mid-1800s and early 1900s, respectively.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> Expansion around [[Ontario]] occurred since early reports in 1890 and 1905. Explanations given include infrequent winter storms in the 20th century, expanded forest habitats, and the wrens taking advantage of urban areas containing feeders, especially in winter.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/>\n\nCarolina wrens adapt to various habitats. Natural habitats include various types of woodland such as [[oak]] hardwoods and mixed oak-pine woodlands, [[ash tree|ash]] and [[elm tree|elmwoods]], hickory-oak woodlands with a healthy amount of tangled undergrowth.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\"/> The preferred habitats are [[riparian forests]], [[shrubland|brushy edges]], [[swamp]]s, overgrown [[farmland]]s, and [[suburban]] yards with abundant thick shrubs and trees, and parks.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\"/> It has an affinity for dilapidated buildings and unkempt yards in man-made areas.<ref name=\"Dunne\"/> Subspecies ''burleighi'' and ''neophilus'' inhabit [[slash pine]] and [[Sabal|palmettos]].<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\"/>\n\n==Behavior==\n\n===Song and calls===\nCarolina wrens sing year round and at any point during the daytime, with the exception of performing during the most harsh weather conditions.<ref name=\"Dunne\"/> The birds are also the only species in the [[Certhiidae]] family that neither sings in duet nor has their song control regions affect repertoire size.<ref name=\"Nealen00\">{{cite journal|author1=Nealen, Paul M. |author2=Perkel, David J. |year=2000|title=Sexual Dimorphism in the Song System of the Carolina Wren (''Thryothorus ludovicianus'')|journal=The Journal of Comparative Neurology|volume=418|issue=4|pages=346\u2013360|pmid=10701831|doi=10.1002/(sici)1096-9861(20000313)418:3<346::aid-cne8>3.3.co;2-b }}</ref> Males alone sing, and have a repertoire of at least twenty different phrase patterns and on average, thirty two.<ref name=\"Nealen00\"/><ref name=\"Elliott2\">{{cite book|last=Elliott|first=Lang|title=Music of the Birds: A Celebration of Bird Song|publisher= Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|year=1999|page=[https://archive.org/details/musicofbirdscele0000elli/page/30 30]|url=https://archive.org/details/musicofbirdscele0000elli|url-access=registration|isbn=978-0618006977}}</ref> One of these patterns is repeated for several minutes, and although the male's song can be repeated up to twelve times, the general number of songs range from three to five times in repetition. While singing, the tail of the birds is pointed downward. Some general vocalizations have been transcribed as ''teakettle-teakettle-teakettle'' and ''cheery-cheery-cheery''.<ref name=\"Bent\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\"/> Various descriptions of the ''teakettle'' song include ''whee-udel, whee-udel, whee-udel'', ''che-wortel, che-wortel'' and ''t\u00fartee-t\u00fartee-t\u00fartee'' and familiar names and phrases such as ''sweet heart, sweet heart'', ''come to me, come to me'', ''sweet William'', and ''Richelieu, Richelieu''.<ref name=\"Bent\"/>\n\nMales are capable of increasing their repertoire through song learning, but due to their sedentary nature and territorial defense habits, the song learning must occur within the first three months of life.<ref name=\"Morton87\"/> Geographic barriers affect song repertoire size from male wrens, as one study indicated that distances separated as close as {{convert|3|km}} by water barriers can have the same effect as that of a distance of {{convert|145|km}} in the mainland with no barriers.<ref name=\"Morton87\">{{cite journal|author=Morton, Eugene S.|year=2005|title=The Effects of Distance and Isolation on Song-type Sharing in the Carolina Wren|journal=Wilson Bulletin|volume=99|issue=4|pages=601\u201310|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v099n04/p0601-p0610.pdf|doi=}}</ref>\n\nFemale Carolina wrens possess song control regions that would appear to make them capable of singing with repertoires like the male. Due to vocalizations that they occasionally make with the male, it has been suggested that song perception plays a role and is of behavioral relevance.<ref name=\"Nealen00\"/>\n\n[[File:Carolina Wren (7318066894).jpg|thumb|left|Carolina wren on Rutland Township Forest Preserve]]\nDifferent subspecies have variations in songs and calls, such as ''miamensis'' having a more rapid song that contains more notes than the races that are further north.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n\nTheir songs can be confused with the [[Kentucky warbler]]. The song patterns are similar, but is of a different quality, as the warbler's songs is described as richer, with more ringing and a hurried pace.<ref name=\"Dunne\"/> Other bird species that have their songs described as akin to the wrens are the [[Colaptes|flicker]], [[Baltimore oriole]], [[grey catbird]], and more specifically the ''peto, peto, peto'' calls of the [[tufted titmouse]], and whistles of the [[northern cardinal]].<ref name=\"Bent\"/> Occasionally, the wrens mimic other species; in [[Pennsylvania]] this trait has caused the bird also to be known as the 'mocking wren'.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n\n===Sexual selection===\nA 2006 study suggested that the correlation of tail length and body size in males, wing length in females, and lifespan for both sexes were signs of individual quality, and the wrens of high quality tend to mate with like individuals. The courting and antagonistic encounters that involve the tail fanning and wing drooping was suggested to be a possible signaling use. Age and life experience are not thought of as significant for potential mates due to their relatively short lifespan and sedentary lifestyle. Due to the large size of male wrens and the male's vigor in defending its territory, intrasexual selection was given as a possible explanation for the sexual dimorphism.<ref name=\"Haggerty\"/>\n\n===Territorial and predator defense===\nBoth sexes are involved in defending the territory. One aspect of territorial defense involves identifying the proximity of the threat based on the loudness of bird song as well as the level of degradation of the calls. In experiments involving playback, the wrens are capable of discriminating between degraded and undegraded songs, as well as degraded songs in the same acoustic conditions, and can detect changes of acoustic properties within their territories, such as songs under foliage.<ref name=\"Naguib95\">{{cite journal|author=Naguib, Marc|year=1995|title=Ranging by Song in Carolina Wrens (''Thryothorus ludovicianus''): Effects of Environmental Acoustics and Strength of Song Degradation|journal=Behaviour|volume=133|issue=7|pages=541\u2013559|url=http://www.unc.edu/home/rhwiley/pdfs/EnvironAcousticsCW.pdf|doi=10.1163/156853996x00206}}</ref> Song degradation can also be used to determine the proximity of potential intruders. If the song of a bird appears to be degraded, the wrens will assume that the threat is distant and not respond; if the song is not degraded, they respond by attacking.<ref name=\"Richards\">{{cite journal|author=Richards, Douglas G.|year=1981|title=Estimation of the Distance of Singing Conspecifics by the Carolina Wren|journal=The Auk|volume=98|issue=1|pages=127\u201333|url=http://www.unc.edu/home/rhwiley/pdfs/Richards1981Distance.pdf|jstor=4085615}}</ref> Not all birds within their territory are potential enemies. Some species of birds that are neighbors are designated as 'dear-enemies' by the wrens, and the responses to neighbors and intruders in their territories differ by the season. In spring, the wrens respond more aggressively toward neighbors, though in the fall, no major discrepancy in responses is shown.<ref name=\"Hyman\">{{cite journal|author=Hyman, Jeremy|year=2005|title=Seasonal Variation in Response to Neighbors and Strangers by a Territorial Songbird|journal=Ethology|volume=111|issue=10|pages=951\u201361|url=http://www.unc.edu/~rhwiley/pdfs/Hyman2005.pdf|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2005.01104.x}}</ref> When protecting their nest, alarm calls are the general response. The wrens judge the size of the potential threat, such as a [[blue jay]] and avoid the risk of injury when attacking.<ref name=\"D'Orazio\">{{cite journal|author1=D'Orazio, Kelly |author2=Neudorf, Diane L. H. |year=2008|title=Nest Defense by Carolina Wrens|journal=The Wilson Journal of Ornithology|volume=120|issue=3|pages=467\u201372|jstor=20456180|doi=10.1676/06-149.1 }}</ref> Countersinging produced by intruder birds is more likely to be taken as an aggressive threat to male Carolina wrens.<ref name=\"Hyman2\">{{cite journal|author=Hyman, Jeremy|year=2003|title=Countersinging as a signal of aggression in a territorial songbird|journal=Animal Behaviour|volume=65|issue=6|pages=1179\u201385|url=http://www.unc.edu/home/rhwiley/pdfs/Hyman1.pdf|doi=10.1006/anbe.2003.2175}}</ref>\n\nBoth males and females utilize calls in alarm situations, especially in territorial disputes and encounters with predators. Males alone produce the ''cheer'' call, which can sound indistinct. In southern regions of their range, the sound males use in alarm disputes is a ringing ''pink'' or ''p'dink'' sound. Females are the only ones that can perform the paired ''dit-dit'' or chatter sounds. The former can be used in territorial disputes with predators, and with at least northern populations the songs are used in alternation with the males ''cheer'' chant. The chatter is used exclusively with territorial encounters with male song, and the song can either follow or overlap her mate's song.<ref name=\"Nealen00\"/><ref name=\"Elliott\">{{cite book|last=Elliott|first=Lang|title=Know Your Bird Sounds: Songs and calls of yard, garden, and city birds|publisher=Stackpole Books|year=2004|page=29|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ChyiBZr6GU8C&pg=PA28|isbn=978-0811729635}}</ref>\n\n===Feeding===\nCarolina wrens spend the majority of their time on or near the ground searching for food, or in tangles of vegetation and vines. They also probe bark crevices on lower tree levels, or pick up leaf-litter in order to search for prey. Their diet consists of invertebrates, such as [[beetles]], [[Hemiptera|true bugs]], [[grasshopper]]s, [[katydid]]s, [[spider]]s, [[ant]]s, [[bee]]s, and [[wasp]]s. Small [[lizard]]s and [[tree frog]]s also make up the carnivorous portion of their diet. Vegetable matter makes up a small percentage of their diets, such as fruit pulp and various [[seed]]s. In the northern portion of their range, they frequent [[bird feeder]]s.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\"/>\n\n===Movement===\nCarolina wrens are wary, and are more often heard than seen. When on the ground, they move in jerky hops pillaging through various objects, whether man-made or natural.<ref name=\"Dunne\"/> While moving abruptly, they pause momentarily for chattering or singing.<ref name=\"Bent\">{{cite journal|author=Bent, Arthur C.|year=1948|title=Life Histories of North American Nuthatches, Wrens, Thrashers, and their Allies: Order Passeriformes|journal=Bulletin of the United States National Museum|volume=|issue=195|pages=205\u201316|doi=10.5479/si.03629236.195.1|hdl=10088/10012|hdl-access=free}}</ref>  When stationary, they move in twitched motions, jerking their breast around.<ref name=\"Dunne\"/> They also sun- or sand-bathe.<ref name=\"Hauser\">{{cite journal|author=Hauser, Doris C.|year=1957|title=Some Obversations of Sun-bathing in Birds|journal=The Wilson Bulletin|volume=69|issue=1|pages=259\u201365|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v069n01/p0078-p0090.pdf|doi=}}</ref> The wrens also displays a skittish behavior when encountered by [[human]]s, as they can be seen thrusting off into cover slowly if approaching is detected. However, they occasionally seek out humans that are near, so long as there is no movement from them.<ref name=\"Bent\"/> Other movements involve being capable of crawling like a [[Treecreeper|creeper]] and hanging upside-down like a [[nuthatch]].<ref name=\"Dunne\"/>\n\nFlights are generally of short duration, rapid, low-leveled, and wavelike. The wings during flight are flapped rapidly, and are frequently used during foraging. They are also capable of flying vertically from the base of a tree to the top in a single wing assisted bound.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Dunne\">{{cite book|last=Dunne|first=Pete|title=Pete Dunne's Essential Field Guide Companion: A Comprehensive Resource for Identifying North American Birds|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|year=2006|page=479|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ISgKT2ehj7oC&pg=PA511|isbn=978-0-300-09059-8}}</ref>\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Carolina Wren nesting in a duck box - Flickr - Andrea Westmoreland.jpg|thumb|Carolina wren nesting in a duck nestbox.]]\nCarolina wrens are both genetically and socially [[monogamy|monogamous]] and will usually mate for life.  Mate changing is rare,<ref name=\"Haggerty\"/> and there has been one possible observation of polygamy.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> During the winter season, males are more responsible for guarding the territory. Females vary in succeeding to maintain winter territories without a mate.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> It has been suggested that the possibility of desertion and decline in care-taking from males along with the need for security in resources year-round prevent extra pair copulations from females, as the mortality rate for Carolina wrens peaks during the winter.<ref name=\"Haggerty&Morton\">{{cite journal|author1=Haggerty, Thomas M. |author2=Morton, Eugene M. |author3=Fleischer, Robert C. |year=2001|title=Genetic Monogamy in Carolina Wrens (''Thryothorus ludovicianus'')|jstor=4089770|journal=The Auk|volume=118|issue=1|pages=215\u201319|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v118n01/p00215-p00219.pdf|doi=10.1093/auk/118.1.215}}</ref> Along with thermoregulatory benefits, [[Bird#Resting and roosting|roosting]] is thought to reinforce pair-bonding and prevent divorce between mates.<ref name=\"Labinsky\">{{cite journal|author1=Labinsky, Ronald F. |author2=Arnett Jr., John E. |year=2006|title=Pair Roosting of Carolina Wrens (''Thryothorus ludovicianus'')|journal=The Wilson Journal of Ornithology|volume=118|issue=4|pages=566\u2013569|url=|doi=10.1676/05-109.1|jstor=20455927}}</ref>\n\nThe nests are arch-shaped structures with a side entrance and built of dried plants or strips of bark, as well as horsehair, string, wool and snake sloughs. Males obtain nesting materials while the females remains at the site to construct the nest. Nests are located in fragmented or complete cavities in trees, or in man-made structures such as bird-boxes, buildings, tin cans, mailboxes or unorthodox places such as pockets of hanging jackets in sheds or in a [[tractor]] in everyday use.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Bent\"/> Nests are from {{convert|1|-|3|m|ft|abbr=on}} from the ground and are rarely higher. They occasionally can be built in sloping locations or at ground level.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/>\n\nEgg laying dates and clutch size vary by region; in Texas the time period is from late February to late August, in Iowa it ranges from late April to June.<ref name=\"TAMU\">{{cite web|title=''Thryothorus ludovicianus''|url=http://txtbba.tamu.edu/species-accounts/carolina-wren/|year=2006|work=Texas A&M AgriLifeExtension|publisher=Texas A&M University|accessdate=31 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Jackson\"/> The clutch size is generally 3 to 6 eggs, but can reach as high as seven in Texas.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"TAMU\"/> The eggs are creamy white with brown or reddish-brown spots, and are more heavily marked at the broad end.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> The eggs are incubated by the female for 12\u201316 days. After the young hatch, they are fed exclusively on invertebrates and they fledge in 12\u201314 days. As many as three broods may be raised by a pair in a single breeding season.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/> In one study, three of the 70 fledglings remained or defended territory adjacent to the natal area.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/>\n\nMale and females are involved in the process of provisioning at similar rates throughout most nest stages, with the males providing slightly more in the nestling stages. Both sexes increase their provision rates as the nestlings grow in age.<ref name=\"Neudorf\">{{cite journal|author1=Neudorf, Diane L. H. |author2=Broddick, Mallory J. |author3=Cureton II |author4=James C. |year=2013|title=Parental Provisioning by Carolina Wrens|journal=The Wilson Journal of Ornithology|volume=125|issue=1|pages=179\u2013184|url=|doi=10.1676/12-009.1}}</ref>\n\n==Predation and threats==\n[[Brood parasitism]] by the [[brown-headed cowbird]] is common, with up to 25% of Carolina wren nests being affected in certain regions such as [[Oklahoma]] and [[Alabama]].<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> Cowbird parasitism peaks in April at 41%, and is as low as 8% and 0% in July and August, respectively. Female cowbirds sometimes eject Carolina wren eggs before laying their own, and even if host eggs are retained, the size of cowbird eggs negatively affect the hatching success of wren eggs. As a result, cowbirds may have a significant impact on the reproductive success of wrens.<ref name=\"Brewer15\"/><ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> The feeding rate for cowbird nestlings is higher than wren feeding rates, and some have been raised to independence.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> This also can be detrimental to the survival of wren nestlings.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> A rare instance of brood-parasitism by a [[house finch]] has been recorded.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|journal=The Wilson Journal of Ornithology|volume= 118|issue=3|pages=413\u2013415|year=2006|doi=10.1676/05-102.1 |title=Carolina Wren Nest Successfully Parasitized by House Finch |author1=Wood, Douglas R.  |author2=William A. Carter}}</ref> The rate of brood parasitism is thought to be lower in more natural and concealed nesting locations.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> Body parasites such as the larvae of [[blowflies]] feed on nestlings and the blood loss weakens nestlings.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\">{{cite web|url=http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/bna/species/188/articles/introduction|title=The Birds of North America Online: Carolina Wren}}</ref> Fellow species of wren such as Bewick's wren and the [[winter wren]] compete for nesting locations and food, respectively.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/>\n\nIn [[Virginia]], some Carolina wrens populations show high levels of [[mercury (element)|mercury]] in their blood and this is acquired from feeding all-year-round on spiders.<ref name=\"JacksonEvers\"/>{{#tag:ref|The [[Holston River|North Folk Holston]] and [[Shenandoah River#South Fork Shenandoah River|South River]]s were used in the study and were both contaminated by industrial activity.|group=\"note\"}} Spiders being at a higher [[trophic level]]s contain a higher concentrations of mercury (through [[biomagnification]]) than herbivorous invertebrates. As these wrens are year-round residents, they are at a higher risk than other species to acquire mercury in its blood. Nest abandonment and failure to raise young were more common with higher mercury content.<ref name=\"JacksonEvers\">{{cite journal|author1=Jackson, Alison K. |author2=Evers, David C. |author3=Etterson, Matthew A. |author4=Condon, Anne M. |author5=Folsom, Sarah B. |author6=Detweiler, Jennifer |author7=Schmerfeld, John |author8=Cristol, Daniel A. |year=2011|title=Mercury Exposure Affects the Reproductive Success of a Free-Living Terrestrial Songbird, The Carolina Wren (''Thryothorus ludovicianus'')|journal=The Auk|volume=128|issue=4|pages=759\u2013769|doi=10.1525/auk.2011.11106}}</ref> Exposure, and prolonged periods of cold, ice, and snow is thought to affect the wren nestling and adult populations, respectively.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/> Wrens that outlast those winters reside in sheltered areas during the season.<ref name=\"Bent\"/>\n\nAmong the top predators of adult Carolina wrens are [[Cat predation on wildlife|domestic cats]], and snakes such as the [[timber rattlesnake]].<ref name=\"VJoS\">{{cite journal|author1=Mitchell, Joseph C. |author2=Beck, Ruth A. |year=1992|title=Free-Ranging Domestic Cat Predation on Native Vertebrates in Rural and Native Virginia|journal=Virginia Journal of Science|volume=43|issue=1B|pages=197\u2013208|url=http://www.vacadsci.org/vjsArchives/V43/43-1B/43-197.pdf|doi=}}</ref><ref name=\"GJoS\">{{cite journal|author1=Parmley, Dennis |author2=Parmley, Amanda M. |year=2001 |title=Food Habits of the Canebrake Rattlesnake (''Crotalus horridus atricaudatus'') in Central Georgia |journal=Georgia Journal of Science |volume=59 |issue=4 |pages=172\u201380 |url=http://facstaff.gpc.edu/~jaliff/GA%20Sci%2059-4.pdf#page=16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014054644/http://facstaff.gpc.edu/~jaliff/GA%20Sci%2059-4.pdf |archivedate=2013-10-14 }}</ref> [[Raccoon]]s and [[black rat snake]]s also feed on wren eggs and nestlings.<ref name=\"Demography and Populations\"/>\n\n==In culture==\n[[File:2000 SC Proof.png|thumb|right|140px|South Carolina state quarter]]\nIn 1930, the South Carolina Federated Women's club adopted the Carolina wren as the unofficial state bird over the [[Mourning dove|eastern mourning dove]] and pushed for its official state adoption until 1939, when the South Carolina Legislature named the [[northern mockingbird]] as the state bird. In 1948, the legislature repealed their previous decision, and the wren became the official state bird.<ref name=\"SouthCarolina\">{{cite web|title=South Carolina State Bird \u2013 Thryrothorus ludovicianus|url=http://www.netstate.com/states/symb/birds/sc_carolina_wren.htm|website=|publisher=NetState|accessdate=31 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, the Carolina wren was featured on the back of the South Carolina edition of the [[50 State Quarters]].<ref name=\"TheUS50\">{{cite web|title=The Official South Carolina State Quarter|url=http://www.theus50.com/southcarolina/quarter.php|website=|publisher=TheUS50|accessdate=31 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|1|group=note}}\n\n==References==<!-- WilsonBull18:47 (compare to current Ohio checklist http://www.ohiobirds.org/publications/OBRClist.pdf) -->\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Brattstrom>{{cite journal|author1=Brattstrom, Bayard H.  |author2=Howell, Thomas R. |year=1956|title= The Birds of the Revilla Gigedo Islands, Mexico|journal=[[Condor (journal)|Condor]]|volume=58|issue=2|pages= 107\u2013120|doi=10.2307/1364977|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v058n02/p0107-p0120.pdf|jstor=1364977 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=David>{{cite journal|author1=David, Normand |author2=Dubois, Alain |year=2011|title= The original spellings of ''Thryothorus'' Vieillot, 1816 (Vertebrata, Aves): a correction|url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2011/f/z02918p068f.pdf |journal=[[Zootaxa]]|volume= 2918|pages= 68|doi=10.11646/zootaxa.2918.1.6 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Mann>{{cite journal|author1=Mann, Nigel I.|author2=Barker, F. Keith|author3=Graves, Jeff A.|author4=Dingess-Mann, Kimberly A.|author5=Slater, Peter J.B.|title=Molecular data delineate four genera of ''\"Thryothorus\"'' wrens|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.014|url=http://www.tc.umn.edu/~barke042/pdfs/Mann.et.al06.pdf|year=2006|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=750\u20139|pmid=16750640|access-date=2007-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071202114315/http://www.tc.umn.edu/~barke042/pdfs/Mann.et.al06.pdf#|archive-date=2007-12-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Martinez>{{cite journal|author1=Mart\u00ednez G\u00f3mez |author2=Juan E. |author3=Barber, Bruian R. |author4=Peterson, A. Townsend |title=Phylogenetic position and generic placement of the Socorro Wren (''Thryomanes sissonii'') |doi=10.1642/0004-8038(2005)122[0050:PPAGPO]2.0.CO;2 |url=http://www.specifysoftware.org/Informatics/bios/biostownpeterson/MBP_A_2005.pdf |year=2005 |volume=122 |pages=50 |journal=The Auk |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217114932/http://www.specifysoftware.org/Informatics/bios/biostownpeterson/MBP_A_2005.pdf |archivedate=2008-12-17 |hdl=1808/16612 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Thryothorus ludovicianus|the Carolina wren}}\n{{Wikispecies|Thryothorus ludovicianus}}\n*[http://www.mbr-pwrc.usgs.gov/id/framlst/i7180id.html Identification tips] \u2013 USGS Patuxent Bird Identification InfoCenter\n*[http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/BirdGuide/Carolina_Wren.html Species account] \u2013 Cornell Lab of Ornithology\n*[http://www.birdhouses101.com/carolina-wren.asp About] \u2013 Bird Houses 101\n*[http://www.bird-stamps.org/cspecies/13504200.htm Stamps] \u2013 BirdLife International\n* {{InternetBirdCollection|carolina-wren-thryothorus-ludovicianus|Carolina wren}}\n* {{VIREO|Carolina+Wren|Carolina wren}}\n* [http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/index.php/download_file/view/1296/724/ Sound] \u2013 Florida Museum of Natural History\n\n<!-- see the decent RangeMap at: \"www.natureserve.org\" ....only \"Permanent Resident\" on map-NOTE ( (2) small \"Spots\" of Perm Resident in \"Nicaragua\")-->\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1585636}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:wren, Carolina}}\n[[Category:Thryothorus|Carolina wren]]\n[[Category:Native birds of Eastern Canada]]\n[[Category:Native birds of the Eastern United States]]\n[[Category:Birds of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1790|Carolina wren]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by John Latham (ornithologist)|Carolina wren]]\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carolina_wren"}
{"title_page": "Gabriel Cole (Medal of Honor)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Gabriel Cole\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1831|3|22}}\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|1907|1|7|1831|3|22}}\n|image= US-MOH-1862.png\n| birth_place  = [[Broome County, New York]]\n| death_place  = [[Tustin, Michigan]]\n| placeofburial_label = Place of burial\n| placeofburial = Sherman Township Cemetery, [[Tustin, Michigan]]\n| allegiance    = {{USA}}\n|branch\t={{army|USA}}<br/>[[Union Army]]\n| rank          = [[File:Confederate States of America Corporal-Cavalry.jpg|25px]] [[Corporal]]\n| unit          = {{flagicon|Michigan}} [[5th Michigan Volunteer Cavalry Regiment|5th Regiment, Michigan Volunteer Cavalry]] - Company I\n| battles       = [[American Civil War]]<br/>{{*}} [[Battle of Opequon]]\n| awards        = {{flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n'''Gabriel Cole''' (March 22, 1831 &ndash; January 9, 1907) was a [[Union Army]] soldier during the [[American Civil War]]. He received the [[Medal of Honor]] for gallantry and the capture of the flag of the [[45th Virginia Infantry]] Regiment during the [[Battle of Opequon]] more commonly called the [[Third Battle of Winchester]], [[Virginia]] on September 19, 1864.\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n\u201cThe President of the United States of America, in the name of Congress, takes pleasure in presenting the Medal of Honor to Corporal Gabriel Cole, United States Army, for extraordinary heroism on 19 September 1864, while serving with Company I, 5th Michigan Cavalry, in action at Winchester, Virginia, for capture of flag, during which he was wounded in the leg.\u201d\n\nCorporal Cole was one of two members of the 5th Michigan Cavalry to receive the Medal of Honor for this action. The other was Sgt. [[Henry M. Fox]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of Medal of Honor recipients]]\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n* {{hallofvalor|992}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=992 Military Times Hall of Valor]\n*[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7966586 Findagrave entry]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cole, Gabriel}}\n[[Category:1831 births]]\n[[Category:1907 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Broome County, New York]]\n[[Category:Union Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:People of New York (state) in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People of Michigan in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Gabriel Cole\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1831|3|22}}\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|1907|1|7|1831|3|22}}\n|image= US-MOH-1862.png\n| birth_place  = [[Broome County, New York]]\n| death_place  = [[Tustin, Michigan]]\n| placeofburial_label = Place of burial\n| placeofburial = Sherman Township Cemetery, [[Tustin, Michigan]]\n| allegiance    = {{USA}}\n|branch\t={{army|USA}}<br/>[[Union Army]]\n| rank          = [[File:Confederate States of America Corporal-Cavalry.jpg|25px]] [[Corporal]]\n| unit          = {{flagicon|Michigan}} [[5th Michigan Volunteer Cavalry Regiment|5th Regiment, Michigan Volunteer Cavalry]]\n| battles       = [[American Civil War]]<br/>{{*}} [[Battle of Opequon]]\n| awards        = {{flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n'''Gabriel Cole''' (March 22, 1831 &ndash; January 9, 1907) was a [[Union Army]] soldier during the [[American Civil War]]. He received the [[Medal of Honor]] for gallantry and the capture of the flag of the [[45th Virginia Infantry]] Regiment during the [[Battle of Opequon]] more commonly called the [[Third Battle of Winchester]], [[Virginia]] on September 19, 1864.\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n\u201cThe President of the United States of America, in the name of Congress, takes pleasure in presenting the Medal of Honor to Corporal Gabriel Cole, United States Army, for extraordinary heroism on 19 September 1864, while serving with Company I, 5th Michigan Cavalry, in action at Winchester, Virginia, for capture of flag, during which he was wounded in the leg.\u201d\n\nCorporal Cole was one of two members of the 5th Michigan Cavalry to receive the Medal of Honor for this action. The other was Sgt. [[Henry M. Fox]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of Medal of Honor recipients]]\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n* {{hallofvalor|992}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=992 Military Times Hall of Valor]\n*[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7966586 Findagrave entry]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cole, Gabriel}}\n[[Category:1831 births]]\n[[Category:1907 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Broome County, New York]]\n[[Category:Union Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:People of New York (state) in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People of Michigan in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabriel_Cole_(Medal_of_Honor)"}
